    <nav class="breadcrumb"><a href="/">Home</a> / <a href="/guides/aider-setup">Guides</a> / Getting started with Cowork</nav>
    <h1>Getting started with Claude Cowork</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      Claude Cowork is a desktop app for handing off multi-step tasks — including building small
      apps and websites — without touching a terminal. It works alongside your files and apps,
      which makes it a solid starting point if command-line tools aren't where you want to spend
      your time.
    </p>

    <div class="callout"><strong>Product details change.</strong> Availability, plans, and features vary over time — check Anthropic's official site for the current specifics before you buy.</div>

    <h2>Who it's for</h2>
    <p>
      If you'd rather describe what you want and review the result than work at the command line,
      Cowork fits. You still get real, working output — you just skip the terminal setup.
    </p>

    <h2>Step 1 — Get the desktop app</h2>
    <div class="step">
      <p>Download and install the Claude desktop app from Anthropic's official site, then open it and sign in with your Claude account. Cowork lives inside the desktop app.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Step 2 — Start a task</h2>
    <div class="step">
      <p>Open the Cowork area and describe your goal in plain language, for example:</p>
      <pre><code>Build a simple landing page for my bakery with a menu
section and a contact form, and let me preview it.</code></pre>
      <p>Cowork breaks the work into steps and starts working through them, showing you what it's doing as it goes.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Step 3 — Review before anything happens for real</h2>
    <div class="step">
      <p>
        For anything with consequences — sending a message, publishing, spending money — Cowork asks
        first. Read what it proposes, then approve or redirect. Nothing irreversible happens without
        your say-so.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h2>Step 4 — Iterate</h2>
    <div class="step">
      <p>Not quite right? Just say so in plain words: "make the header green" or "add a second menu column." Cowork adjusts and shows you the result again.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="callout"><strong>Good first projects:</strong> a landing page, a small automation, cleaning up a spreadsheet, or a simple web tool. Save large existing codebases for a terminal tool once you want more control.</div>

    <h2>Is Cowork right for you?</h2>
    <p>
      It's the easiest starting point if you want results without setup, and a flat monthly price
      instead of token math. If you want fine-grained control or the lowest possible cost, a
      terminal tool like Aider may serve you better.
    </p>

